						<div class="postbody">Might also be worth noting, lilypond <a href="http://lilypond.org/doc/v2.19/Documentation/notation/expressive-marks-as-lines" class="postlink">does it with <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">\glissando</tt></a>, which produces a straight line.<br /><br />Somewhat related, I used lilypond to make a <a href="http://rainwarrior.ca/music/coltrane.pdf" class="postlink">score for a saxophone transcrption</a>, and then later wrote an <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i5vyQO81qNc" class="postlink">NES program</a> to play it back. I used lilypond's glissando feature, but I added a custom <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">\glissin</tt> to notate a bend into a note from below (common in this particular piece), and increased the thickness of the lines: <a href="http://rainwarrior.ca/music/coltrane.ly" class="postlink">coltrane.ly</a></div>

